### Node.js Express Transaction Naming for 404 Errors

Source: https://github.com/newrelic/node-newrelic/blob/main/NEWS.md

This snippet addresses an issue with naming Express transactions that result in 404 errors. Previously, transactions for URLs causing 404s were not always correctly normalized. The fix ensures these transactions are consistently reported with a normalized name, such as 'get /'.

```javascript
const express = require('express');
const app = express();
const newrelic = require('newrelic');

// Assume some routes are defined, but this specific route does not exist
// app.get('/existing', (req, res) => res.send('OK'));

// When a request comes in for a non-existent route, Express typically sends a 404.
// Example: GET /nonexistent-page

// Previously, the transaction name might have been inconsistent or incorrect.
// After the fix, the transaction will be reported with a normalized name like 'get /'.
```

